    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>National Briefing | New England: Maine: 1970'S Law Bans Sunday Liquor Sales</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Katie Zezima (NYT)</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Zezima, Katie</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Maine, which has taken over liquor licensing in state from municipalities, will enforce 1970's law making it illegal to sell liquor on Sundays unless approved by municipal referendums (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>It is illegal to buy liquor on Sundays in 135 municipalities because of a 1970's law that the state rediscovered in June, after taking over liquor licensing. In the 1970's, most towns decided that stores could sell liquor on Sundays only if allowed by referendums. Until municipalities act, stores in many cities, including Augusta, Bangor and Portland, cannot sell liquor on Sundays.</p>
        <p>Katie Zezima (NYT)</p>
      </block>
